bution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Peverall  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Peverall","meanings":["Norman, English: relationship name from Old French  <i>Peurel</i> (Latin  <i>Piperellus</i>), a diminutive of Old French  <i>pevre</i> ‘pepper’ (Anglo-Norman French  <i>peivere</i>, Latin  <i>piper</i>), originally perhaps used as a nickname on the Continent but used as a personal name in Anglo-Norman England."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud Peverell had at least 1 son with Robert Turre."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1082–1150":"1082–1150","1120–1216":"1120–1216","–Female":"Surnud","1216":"1216","1120":"1120","1150":"1150","1082":"1082","Blagdon, Somerset, England":"Blagdon, Somerset, England"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1082–1150":"1082–1150","1120–1216":"1120–1216","–Female"